      "comment_id" : 114759748,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "@YuraHoy No runtime type check is being done here even before version 8.  The type had to be added just to satisfy the compiler.  Now the compiler infers the type from the method signature.  See <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/generics/genTypeInference.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/generics/&hellip;</a>"
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 4683411,
        "reputation" : 529,
        "user_id" : 3791510,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9382caf058b2aa742a6d092ec24e6d7f?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
        "display_name" : "marinier",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3791510/marinier"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 1,
      "creation_date" : 1729613267,
      "post_id" : 27524678,
      "comment_id" : 139502770,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "FYI, even with Java 8 (or 21 for that matter) this is still necessary in cases where there is an ambiguity. E.g., I have two methods with the same name, one takes 2 <code>Runnable</code>s and the other takes 2 <code>Callable</code>s. Using just <code>any()</code> for both args was ambiguous so I had to use the accepted answer&#39;s approach."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 405939,
      "reputation" : 12495,
      "user_id" : 775138,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 66,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/XAKUy.jpg?s=256",
