    "last_activity_date" : 1418816127,
    "creation_date" : 1418816127,
    "answer_id" : 27524678,
    "question_id" : 7917635,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Using Java 8, you can simply use <code>any()</code> (assuming static import) without argument or type parameter because of enhanced type inference.  The compiler now knows from the target type (the type of the method argument) that you actually mean <code>Matchers.&lt;AsyncCallback&lt;ResponseX&gt;&gt;any()</code>, which is the pre-Java 8 solution.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 160043,
      "reputation" : 193,
      "user_id" : 379806,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0d97a0e087ae23bcb5a11459fcf776ed?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "JWGS",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/379806/jwgs"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 4,
    "last_activity_date" : 1459518132,
    "creation_date" : 1459518132,
    "answer_id" : 36357903,
    "question_id" : 7917635,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Further to thSoft's answer putting the qualified call to any() in method meant I could remove the qualification since the return type allowed inference:</p>\n\n<pre><code>private HashMap&lt;String, String&gt; anyStringStringHashMap() {\n    return Matchers.any();\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
