      "creation_date" : 1610536047,
      "post_id" : 62179717,
      "comment_id" : 116163140,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "It was my problem too. I use generally a static import for org.mockito.Mockito.*, but in this case only the when() method could be used without qualification, the any() method needs the qualification."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 4779952,
      "reputation" : 1522,
      "user_id" : 3862024,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 100,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/HYIdB.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "gagarwa",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3862024/gagarwa"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 6,
    "last_activity_date" : 1714681850,
    "last_edit_date" : 1714681850,
    "creation_date" : 1591207599,
    "answer_id" : 62179717,
    "question_id" : 7917635,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>I had a similar problem using Spring <code>Example</code>:</p>\n<pre><code>Mockito.when(repo.findAll(Mockito.&lt;Example&lt;SampleEntity&gt;&gt;any()))\n            .thenReturn(Lists.emptyList());\n</code></pre>\n<p>Here, you have to use qualification, b/c findAll method can take multiple types, like <code>Sort</code> and <code>Iterable</code>.  You can also use <code>Mockito.any(Example.class)</code> of course with the type safety warning.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1119690,
      "reputation" : 23190,
      "user_id" : 1108305,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 47,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4c16849c5f9444a685f62cdc2a15c3ac?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "M. Justin",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1108305/m-justin"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1618470778,
    "last_edit_date" : 1618470778,
    "creation_date" : 1618441940,
    "answer_id" : 67100206,
    "question_id" : 7917635,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Using a qualified generics type with the no-argument <code>any()</code> method works (i.e. <code>ArgumentMatchers.&lt;AsyncCallback&lt;ResponseX&gt;&gt;any()</code>), but can get unwieldy for longer generics expressions.  An alternative is to put a no-argument <code>any()</code> call in its own generic method, using the specific generic type as the return type:</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>private static &lt;T&gt; AsyncCallback&lt;T&gt; anyAsyncCallback() {\n  return ArgumentMatchers.any()\n}\n</code></pre>\n<h2>Usage</h2>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>Mockito.verify(mockObject).performCallback(any(), anyAsyncCallback())\n</code></pre>\n"
  } ],
